<p><strong>The Germ That Causes Cancer: Helicobacter pylori</strong></p>
<p><strong>What is Helicobacter pylori?</strong></p>
<p>Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) is a type of bacteria that lives in the stomach. It is the most common bacterial infection in the world, with an estimated 50% of the population infected.</p>
<p><strong>How does H. pylori cause cancer?</strong></p>
<p>H. pylori is a known carcinogen, which means it can cause cancer. It does this by damaging the cells in the stomach lining, which can lead to inflammation. This inflammation can eventually lead to the development of stomach cancer.</p>
<p><strong>What are the symptoms of H. pylori infection?</strong></p>
<p>Most people with H. pylori infection do not have any symptoms. However, some people may experience:</p>
<ul>
<li>Stomach pain</li>
<li>Nausea</li>
<li>Vomiting</li>
<li>Diarrhea</li>
<li>Weight loss</li>
<li>Fatigue</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How is H. pylori infection diagnosed?</strong></p>
<p>H. pylori infection can be diagnosed with a blood test, stool test, or breath test.</p>
<p><strong>How is H. pylori infection treated?</strong></p>
<p>H. pylori infection is typically treated with antibiotics. Treatment usually lasts for 1-2 weeks.</p>
<p><strong>How can I prevent H. pylori infection?</strong></p>
<p>There is no sure way to prevent H. pylori infection. However, following these tips may help to reduce your risk:</p>
<ul>
<li>Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water before eating or handling food.</li>
<li>Cook food thoroughly.</li>
<li>Avoid drinking unpasteurized milk or water.</li>
<li>Do not share food or drinks with someone who has H. pylori infection.</li>
</ul>